---

What is the experiment about?

This experiment teaches how to create RESTful web services using Spring Boot.
You will learn how to create, read, update, and delete data (CRUD) and test it using Postman.


---

Aim (Simple Words):

To build and test a REST API in Spring Boot that can add, show, change, and delete student data.


---

Tools Required (Simple Words):

JDK 17+ → To run Java

Spring Boot → To easily build web services

Any IDE like IntelliJ, Eclipse, or STS → To write code

Postman → To test the API

Maven → To manage dependencies and build the project



---

Theory (Simple Words):

REST is a way to create APIs using simple HTTP methods.

CRUD operations happen through:

GET → Read data

POST → Add new data

PUT → Update data

DELETE → Remove data


Spring Boot gives easy annotations like:

@RestController

@GetMapping

@PostMapping

@PutMapping

@DeleteMapping


These help create APIs quickly.

Data is sent and received in JSON format.



---

Source Code Summary (Simple Words):

Student.java → A simple class with id, name, and age.

StudentController.java → Contains all CRUD methods.

RestApiApplication.java → Main class to start the Spring Boot app.



---

Testing in Postman (Simple Words):

GET → Show all students

POST → Add a new student

PUT → Change student details

DELETE → Remove a student



---

Expected Output (Simple Words):

All CRUD tasks should work properly, and you should see correct JSON results in Postman.


---

Result (Simple Words):

The REST API was successfully created and tested. Students understood how CRUD operations work in Spring Boot and how to check them in Postman.


